I. Evaluate expected significance without any event selection.¶

Use Poisson statistics for significance calculation

$N_{higgs} = 100$ and $N_{QCD} = 20000$. We know the background will be having a Poisson distribution(with mean of $N_{QCD}$). THe Higgs Boson signal will be $N_{higgs} + N_{QCD} = 20100$

In [4]:
signal = 20100
mean = 20000
prob = stats.poisson.cdf(signal,mean)
sigma = stats.norm.ppf(prob)
sigma
Out[4]:
0.7112259282313185

The sigma value is only 0.711 right now without any event selection

The value of approximation $N_{Higgs} / \sqrt{N_{QCD}}$ is given by $100 / \sqrt{20000}$

In [5]:
100 / 20000 **(1/2)
Out[5]:
0.7071067811865475

The value of approximation $N_{Higgs} / \sqrt{N_{QCD}}$ is around 0.7071, very close to the significance 0.7112

II. Identify mass cuts to optimize the expected significance.¶

  • Try different mass cuts systematically
  • Evaluate expected significance for each set of mass cuts
  • Identify the set of mass cuts which give you the highest significance.

Let's first define a function that takes upper and lower bound of the cuts of an data attribute and returns expected siginificance of the data inside the cuts to make future calculation more convenient.

In [6]:
def data_cut(low,high,attribute):
    higgs_cut = higgsData[attribute][higgsData[attribute]>low]
    higgs_cut = higgs_cut[higgs_cut<high]
    qcd_cut = qcdData[attribute][qcdData[attribute]>low]
    qcd_cut = qcd_cut[qcd_cut<high]
    
    #normalize data
    higgs_n = 100 * len(higgs_cut)/len(higgsData[attribute])
    qcd_n = 20000 * len(qcd_cut)/len(qcdData[attribute])
    #calculating the significance in mass cuts.
    #sig = abs(stats.norm.ppf(1-stats.poisson.cdf(higgs_n+qcd_n,qcd_n)))
    sig = stats.norm.ppf(stats.poisson.cdf(higgs_n+qcd_n,qcd_n))
    print(f"Significance for {attribute} from {low} to {high} is given by {sig}")
    return higgs_cut, qcd_cut, sig

Now we try different mass cuts systematically. From the plot, the mass of higgs data seems to gather centered around halfway between 100 and 150. Let's take 125 as the center, and gradually increase our bounds for cuts to see where the maximum significance occurs

def MakingPlots(attribute, title):
    plt.title(f'{title} distrubution')
    plt.hist(higgsData[attribute], bins=75, alpha=0.5, density=True, label='Higgs')
    plt.hist(qcdData[attribute], bins=75, alpha=0.5, density=True, label='QCD')
    plt.legend(prop={"size":20})
    plt.xlabel(f'{attribute}',fontsize = 16)
    plt.ylabel('Density',fontsize = 16)
    plt.show()

  • Set B with your optimal mass cuts
    • Can you identify another feature to further improve your expected signifiance?

We can define another function, that prints the significance of the cuts of an given feature corresponding to our optimal mass cuts, and another function that plots the histograms of features with optimal cuts.

In [12]:
def data_cut_2(attribute):
    higgs_cut = higgsData[higgsData['mass']>123]
    higgs_cut = higgs_cut[higgs_cut['mass']<127]
    higgs_cut = higgs_cut[attribute]
    qcd_cut = qcdData[qcdData['mass']>123]
    qcd_cut = qcd_cut[qcd_cut['mass']<127]
    qcd_cut = qcd_cut[attribute]
    #normalize data
    higgs_n = 100 * len(higgs_cut)/len(higgsData[attribute])
    qcd_n = 20000 * len(qcd_cut)/len(qcdData[attribute])
    #calculating the significance in mass cuts.
    sig = abs(stats.norm.ppf(1-stats.poisson.cdf(higgs_n+qcd_n,qcd_n)))
    print(f"Significance for {attribute} from mass of {123} to {127} is given by {sig}")
    return higgs_cut, qcd_cut, sig
In [13]:
def MakingOptPlots(higgs, qcd, title): #function that plots histogram given optimal mass
    plt.title(f'{title} distrubution with optimal cuts')
    plt.hist(higgs, bins=75, alpha=0.5, density=True, label='Higgs')
    plt.hist(qcd, bins=75, alpha=0.5, density=True, label='QCD')
    plt.legend(prop={"size":20})
    plt.xlabel(f'{title}',fontsize = 16)
    plt.ylabel('Density',fontsize = 16)

In previous section, we classify ee3, d2, t3, t2, KtDeltaR as being most discriminative after our mass cuts. So we can try out few cuts systematically on each of them and find out which one gives highest significance.

def data_cut_3(attribute,low,high,higgs,qcd): #function for our second cut after mass cut
    higgs_cut = higgs[higgs>=low]
    higgs_cut = higgs_cut[higgs_cut<high]
    qcd_cut = qcd[qcd>low]
    qcd_cut = qcd_cut[qcd_cut<high]
    
    #normalize data
    higgs_n = 100 * len(higgs_cut)/len(higgsData['mass'])
    qcd_n = 20000 * len(qcd_cut)/len(qcdData['mass'])
    #calculating the significance.
    sig = stats.norm.ppf(stats.poisson.cdf(higgs_n+qcd_n,qcd_n))
    print(f"Significance for {attribute} from {low} to {high} is given by {sig}")
    return higgs_cut, qcd_cut, sig
